    <mj-section css-class="light-wrap" padding-bottom="20px">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text> Dear Campus Community, </mj-text>
        <mj-text> In times of uncertainty regarding immigration, it’s important to know where to turn for accurate information and support resources. We want to remind our campus community of Cal Poly Humboldt’s <a href="https://www.humboldt.edu/immigration">Immigration Rights and Resources website</a>, which serves as a central hub for guidance, legal services, Dreamer student resources, and updates from the California State University. </mj-text>
        <mj-text> We encourage everyone to review the site and share it widely. It includes a Quick Guide <a href="https://www.humboldt.edu/sites/default/files/marketing-communications/2025-04/immigration-quickguidecard.pdf">card</a> and <a href="https://www.humboldt.edu/sites/default/files/immigration/2025-05/immigrationquickguideflyer.pdf">flyer</a> outlining what to do if you encounter immigration officials on campus, as well as contacts and tools to help protect your rights and privacy.</mj-text>
        <mj-text> If your office or department would like additional copies of the Quick Guide cards, please email Marketing & Communications at <a href="mailto:marcom@humboldt.edu">marcom@humboldt.edu</a> to request more.</mj-text>
        <mj-text> Cal Poly Humboldt remains committed to fostering a community where everyone—regardless of immigration status—feels safe, informed, and empowered. Please take a moment to explore these resources and know that you are not alone. By staying informed and connected, we can continue building a more inclusive and supportive campus for everyone. </mj-text>
        <mj-text>Warmly,</mj-text>
        <mj-image src="https://mailings.humboldt.edu/general/signatures/capps-sig.png" width="175px" alt="Sherie Gordon's signature" align="left" padding-top="20px" />
